metadata.name: NEW TERRITORIES #86
metadata.description:
On desktop, open project in live view
Rotate and zoom with the mouse to explore the model
Click ‚ÄúS‚Äù to download STL 3D model file
Click ‚ÄúP‚Äù to download PNG file (3600x3600)


New Territories

New Territories is the sequel to Cityblocks. In this series, urban ensembles are generated with a simple click. With each iteration appears a new densely built city block. Graced with impeccable geometrical lines, devoid of any human presence, these buildings remind us of brutalist utopias like Le Corbusier‚Äôs Cit√© radieuse or Niemeyer‚Äôs Brasilia. But despite their clearly modernist feel, there is something hauntingly primitive about them. They could be either New Mexican adobe pueblos, Minoan palaces, or Turkish troglodyte dwellings. Both carved and sculpted, these Ghormenghasts of concrete float in a realm out of time, like in some architect‚Äôs dream.

The purpose of this creative work is to generate 3D architectural projects that could be implemented in the real world. The accelerating lives that we live, complicated by growing and unpredictable environmental crises, call for an enhanced capacity to come up quickly with new architectural solutions adapted to different contexts. From computer assisted design to 3D printing, from augmented reality to real-life housing, from sculpture to architecture, this work aims at bridging the gap between the virtual and the tangible.

Working as a visual artist, David Umemoto draws inspiration from his training as an architect. He has been using low-tech methods for a long time, refining his talent for elegant simple shapes and combinatory constructions. Now, poured concrete and home-made moulds are giving way to zero-gravity rotating models. The skills he developed while working with real objects find a new playground in the virtual realm.

metadata.name: Los Osos 2422 #1877
metadata.description:
# Los Osos 2422

I was working on the next EmProps release when accidentally I opened a link to a bear utopic civilization through their existing metaverse. Or should I say "metabears"?

Enter Los Osos 2422. 

Four hundred years into the future bears live in a peaceful civilization heavily inspired by the generative art movement of our times. They are organized in districts that are sustained by bamboo, salmon, berries, and art! Los Osos are black, grizzly, panda, and polar, yet there are no distinctions between species; it's not like they were humans. 

They have different occupations but frequently bears change jobs giving birth to the most eclectic looks.

I took my sketchbook out to capture what I could and started drawing but my presence pissed them off. Ninjas, luchadores, and even a cybearpunk forced me to escape.  Is that a live gummy bear or am I just hungry? The story will continue...

-- 

Los Osos 2422 is a PFP art piece composed of 320 hand-made drawings made as an homage to the nascent generative art current fueled by Tezos blockchain technology in 2022. It features hundreds of references to artists and pieces in several generative and non-generative fields.

The project combines the assets together using a custom open-source algorithm that allows them to stack with the positioning in front and behind the character to create possibilities like shirt collars or hats, dynamic tinting to have hoodies or glasses with different colors, exceptions to give them laser eyes or a green apple in front of the face, complex set-ups to have different versions for some of the outfits, and chance control to allow precise control over the features.

--

Press 'S' on the keyboard to save it as an 1800 x 1800 pixels PNG.

metadata.name: Illuminations #281
metadata.description:
Created for the FxHash Turns One week - Thank you FxHash for all the opportunities you have given generative artists and collectors, and thank you to everyone who makes, and collects, the great art here. Here are a few celebratory generative effects which come from my 2022 experiments on random walks through color and space.

There are 5 different burst patterns (Whirligig, Sky Ripple, Confetti, Classic, Sparkler) and the Cocktail type brings them all together (somewhat chaotically)

To continue with the display after it stops press c

To switch to tranquil mode press t - You will want to try this out when you have a minute

To switch back to live mode press v

To stop the display process press x

To save a 2800x2800 jpg press s

Made with p5.js - all proceeds and royalties assigned to the Processing Foundation (who also deserve a big thank you)

metadata.name: Vormenspel #9
metadata.description:
Schetsboek contained an algorithm that scribbled a small piece of art (800x800 px).

In this artwork, I used that algorithm in two systems (in a grid and/or layered), taking it to new dimensions, but still focused on composition and the interplay of simple shapes and colors. 

It reminds me to stay playful and enjoy the little things in life.  

This is a free mint for holders of schetsboek.

metadata.name: Sublime #76
metadata.description:
We are always running, for a purpose/without a purpose; towards a goal/without a goal; mindfully/mindlessly, and we change; transformed by the situations surrounding us, transformed by our own footprints in our everyday lives. Sometimes its hard to look at our own selves, ashamed of the moth that we might have become. And sometimes we are proud, of the beautiful butterfly that we might have become. However, let us not forget that change is inevitable. And it lies within us - the power to change ourselves and how we allow ourselves to be shaped by the never ending feedback effects of our society. Let us all change for a better tomorrow. 

- - - - - - - - -

Energy can neither be created nor be destroyed. But it always changes from one form to the other. Starting with this half forgotten statement from my childhood school memories, driven by this idea of constant change as an invariance in all live systems - I present before you, Sublime. 

Made with love in cables.gl harnessing the power of noise!

Press & hold 'p' for performance.(The feedback system can be a bit heavy sometimes.)
Press 's' to save a screenshot.

metadata.name: Code/Painting Composition #5
metadata.description:
"Code/Painting Composition" is an exciting new NFT collection that seamlessly merges the creative arts of image composition and coding algorithms. This groundbreaking collection, painted on Procreate, has been meticulously crafted layer-by-layer using P5js to create a truly unique and unparalleled piece of digital art.

This collection is my first collaboration between image composition and coding algorithms and was made possible by the brilliant minds behind it, who have been working tirelessly to create something truly special. With special thanks to the Artcode Wizard, this NFT collection has something special in store for everyone.

What makes Code-Composition so unique is the way it seamlessly blends two seemingly disparate disciplines to create something new entirely. Each piece in this collection is a masterpiece of digital art that combines stunning visuals with coding algorithms that give each piece a unique character and personality. So, whether you're a collector or a lover of digital art, Code-Composition is a collection that you simply cannot miss out on.

---------------------------------
Press "s" or "S" to download the higher resolution of generated pieces.

metadata.name: COMPACT #1
ASSEMBLING MACHINE #261
metadata.description:
The machine never sleeps.
Build. Construct. Develop. Create. Form. Produce. Generate. Repeat.
---------------
Collectors at the highest tier (125 tez) may claim a signed 8‚Äùx10‚Äù print of their mint. Please look for details about prints on Twitter (@teaboswell), or contact me directly
---------------
CONTROLS:
A - Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)
S - Download image
Double tap (mobile) - Download image
1-6 - Modify scale (1 = default, 2048 x 2730px, 6 = maximum, 12288 x 16380px (very performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F - Fit to current screen size
G - Toggle grain overlay
L - Toggle background grid lines
B - Cycle border sizes (0 -> 100 -> 200 -> 300px)

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)

metadata.name: Country Spirit I #14
metadata.description:
‚ÄúRaoul Pictor cherche son style‚Ä¶‚Äù (Raoul Pictor is looking for his style‚Ä¶) was launched in Saint-Gall, Switzerland, in 1993. It consists of a Mac LC computer, a 12-inch color screen, and an HP 500C printer.
The program presents an animation in which we can observe an artist, Raoul Pictor, working in his studio. He paints, paces while deep in thought, consults books from his library, plays the piano, and enjoys red wine. The sequence of these activities is non-linear. The canvas is seen from behind, resting on the easel in the center of the room. We are unable to see what is being painted. Once his painting is complete, he picks it up and exits through a side door. It is at this moment that the printer springs into action, delivering his unique, dated, and signed work.
This project has been exhibited in numerous exhibitions around the world. Subsequently, a Flash version, "Raoul Pictor Web Studio," was developed to make it available on the internet (2001). In 2013, for its 20th anniversary, an iOS version, "Raoul Pictor Mega Painter," was developed in collaboration with the great Matthieu Cherubini (mchrbn.net). 
In 2023, for its 30th anniversary, an update seemed necessary to continue the adventure on the fx(hash) platform ‚Äì thank you for making all of this possible! The development of this first fx version (‚ÄúCountry Spirit I‚Äù) was greatly enhanced by the wonderful support and expertise of the sha22.art team as well as our friends. Additional collections are now planned for the near future or special events...

[up_arrow], [space bar] : Painter jumps in first part of animation.

[p], [mouse click], [touch screen] : Save the painting when it is displayed.

metadata.name: Artifice #322
metadata.description:
This series is is about playful obfuscation.

The fxtext article linked on the main profect goes more in-depth into what is meant by that, as well as the events that led to this collection.

5640 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries. Palettes make up a third of the code.

In live mode:
‚ÄòS‚Äô : save as png (3000‚Ää√ó‚Ää3600)
‚ÄôV‚Äô : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‚Äòg=n‚Äô : no grain
‚Äòg=p‚Äô : paper grain
‚Äòh=t‚Äô : high resolution mode, 9000‚Ää√ó10600 (Chrome only, and may take a moment)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append ‚Äú&g=p&h=t‚Äù to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save a png with those settings applied.
